rca 1380","1357":"1357","1400":"1400","1455":"1455","1355":"1355","1375":"1375","1473":"1473","1385":"1385","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","Witherslack, Westmorland, England":"Witherslack, Westmorland, England"},"en":{"about 1380–":"about 1380–Deceased","1375–Male":"1375–Deceased","1380–Male":"1380–Deceased","1385–Female":"1385–Deceased","1400–1473":"1400–1473","1355–Male":"1355–Deceased","1357–Female":"1357–Deceased","about 1380":"about 1380","1357":"1357","1400":"1400","1455":"1455","1355":"1355","1375":"1375","1473":"1473","1385":"1385","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","Witherslack, Westmorland, England":"Witherslack, Westmorland, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Ros","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Enrique, Luis, Jose, Alberto, Eduardo, Rafael, Elena, Fidel, Joaquin, Manuel, Pablo, Ramon.  Southeast Asian Leang, Phon, Lap, Phan, Pho, Saroeun, Sophal, Sophan, Sophea, Tha, Thang, Yen.","Catalan: nickname for someone with blond hair or a fair complexion, ultimately from Latin <i>russus</i>.","Swedish: ornamental name from <i>ros</i> ‘rose’."],"variants":[{"name":"Rus","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Romanian Simion, Grigore, Doina, Dorel, Ilie, Liviu, Petru, Vasile.","Czech, Slovak, and Romanian (of Slavic origin): ethnic name for a Russian, ultimately derived from an Old Norse term meaning ‘oarsman, rower’ (from the root <i>roths-</i>), a reference to the fact that the Russian state was established by Scandinavians who rowed their ships up rivers inland from the Baltic sea. In some cases this may also be origin of the Slovenian and Croatian surname (see 3 below).","Czech: descriptive nickname from the adjective <i>rusý</i> ‘blond’."]},{"name":"Ross","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from one or other of a number of Scottish and English places called Ross or Roos(e), especially Roose (Lancashire) and Roos (East Yorkshire). The placenames derive from a British ancestor of Welsh <i>rhos</i> ‘moor, heath, plain’, which is the sense of the cognate Gaelic word <i>ros</i>. The Scottish surname has at least three origins. First, the Anglo-Norman family from Roos (East Yorkshire) was introduced to Scotland when Robert of Roos, lord of Wark Castle (Northumberland), married Isabella, an illegitimate daughter of King William the Lion. Second, various families took the name from the province of Ross in northern Scotland and other places of that name. Third, there were Norman families in Scotland by the 13th century who probably derived their name from Rots in Normandy (see 2 below). The descendants of Godfrey <i>de Ros</i>, tenant of the de Morville lords of Cunninghame, were major landholders in Ayrshire, and almost certainly took their name from Rots. The Rose family of Kilravock (Nairnshire) may take their name from either of these three (see   Rose  ). The lairds of Balnagown adopted the surname <i>Ross</i> after the earldom of Ross (to which they considered themselves rightful heirs) had passed into other hands through the female line.","English (of Norman origin): habitational name from Rots in Calvados (France), probably named with the ancient Germanic element <i>rod</i> ‘clearing’ (compare   Rhodes  ). This was the original home of a family de Ros, who were established in Kent in 1130 and had major estates in Kent until well into the 13th century.","English: habitational name from Wrose, in Shipley, near Bradford (Yorkshire), with re-spelling of <i>Wr-</i> as <i>R-</i> due to the loss of /w/ before /r/ in early modern English pronunciation. The spelling <i>Wrose</i> is no longer current. The placename derives from Old English <i>wrāse</i> ‘knot, something twisted’, referring to the steep-sided hill on which the settlement stands, with the sense ‘broken or twisting hill’."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":2,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705197,"age":75,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When John de Ros was born about 1380, in Witherslack, Westmorland, England, his father, Richard de Ros, was 27 and his mother, Joan Thornburgh, was 25. He had at least 1 son with unknown."},"et":{"about 1380–":"umbes 1380–Surnud","1375–Male":"1375–Surnud","1380–Male":"1380–Surnud","1385–Female":"1385–Surnud","1400–1473":"1400–1473","1355–Male":"1355–Surnud","1357–Female":"1357–Surnud","about 1380":"umbes 1380","1357":"1357","1400":"1400","1455":"1455","1355":"1355","1375":"1375","1473":"1473","1385":"1385","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","Witherslack, Westmorland, England":"Witherslack, Westmorland, England"},"fi":{"about 1380–":"noin 1380–Kuollut","1375–Male":"1375–Kuollut","1380–Male":"1380–Kuollut","1385–Female":"1385–Kuollut","1400–1473":"1400–1473","1355–Male":"1355–Kuollut","1357–Female":"1357–Kuollut","about 1380":"noin 1380","1357":"1357","1400":"1400","1455":"1455","1355":"1355","1375":"1375","1473":"1473","1385":"1385","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","Witherslack, Westmorland, England":"Witherslack, Westmorland, England"},"fr":{"about 1380–":"environ 1380–Décédé","1375–Male":"1375–Décédé","1380–Male":"1380–Décédé","1385–Female":"1385–Décédée","1400–1473":"1400–1473","1355–Male":"1355–Décédé","1357–Female":"1357–Décédée","about 1380":"environ 1380","1357":"1357","1400":"1400","1455":"1455","1355":"1355","1375":"1375","1473":"1473","1385":"1385","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","Witherslack, Westmorland, England":"Witherslack, Westmorland, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Lorsque John de Ros est né environ 1380, à Witherslack, Westmorland, Angleterre, son père, Richard de Ros, avait 27 ans et sa mère, Joan Thornburgh, avait 25 ans. Il a eu au moins 1 fils avec unknown."},"de":{"about 1380–":"um 1380–Verstorben","1375–Male":"1375–Verstorben","1380–Male":"1380–Verstorben","1385–Female":"1385–Verstorben","1400–1473":"1400–1473","1355–Male":"1355–Verstorben","1357–Female":"1357–Verstorben","about 1380":"um 1380","1357":"1357","1400":"1400","1455":"1455","1355":"1355","1375":"1375","1473":"1473","1385":"1385"